05095nam a22007815i 9780812292909DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979578291  a97808122929097 a10.9783/97808122929092doi  a(DE-B1597)469630  a(OCoLC)948780236  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBP68.A1bC66 2016 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a946.022211 aCook, Karoline P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForbidden Passages :bMuslims and Moriscos in Colonial Spanish America /cKaroline P. Cook. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b5 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Early Modern Americas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Who Were the Moriscos? -- t2. Into the Atlantic -- t3. Forbidden Crossings -- t4. “These Hidden Heretics” -- t5. Healers and Diviners -- t6. “Polvos del Gran Turco” -- t7. Honor, Lineage, Ovandina -- t8. Images of Muslims and Moriscos in Spanish America -- tEpilogue -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, Spanish authorities restricted emigration to the Americas to those who could prove they had been Catholic for at least three generations. In doing so, they hoped to instill religious orthodoxy in the colonies and believed Muslim converts, or Moriscos, would hamper efforts to convert indigenous people to Catholicism. Nevertheless, Moriscos secretly made the treacherous journey across the ocean, settling in the forbidden territories and influencing the nature of Spanish colonialism. Once landed, Morisco men and women struggled to define and practice their religion or pursue their trades, all while experiencing increasing anxiety about their place in the emerging Spanish empire. Many Moriscos were accused by authorities of descending from Muslims or practicing Islam in secret and turned to the courts to assert their legitimacy.Forbidden Passages is the first book to document and evaluate the impact of Moriscos in the early modern Americas. Through close examination of sources that few historians have used—some one hundred cases of individuals brought before the secular, ecclesiastical, and inquisitorial courts—Karoline P. Cook shows how legislation and attitudes toward Moriscos in Spain assumed new forms and meanings in colonial Spanish America. Moriscos became not simply individuals struggling to join a community that was increasingly hostile to them but also symbols that sparked authorities' fears about maintaining religious purity in the face of territorial expansion. Cook reveals how Morisco emigrants shined a light on the complicated question of what it meant to be Spanish in the New World.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMoriscoszLatin AmericaxHistoryy16th century. 0aMoriscoszLatin AmericaxHistoryy17th century. 0aMuslimszLatin AmericaxHistoryy16th century. 0aMuslimszLatin AmericaxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066591840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229290940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812292909423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812292909.jpg  a978-3-11-066591-8  Universit